<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Movement Attrition-- and What it can do For You<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.80)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9256'>Anthony "tonies_gin" gin</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9256&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 5, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> -- First a couple of side notes:  I do believe I timed out writing this so I apologize if I posted this twice.  Also this is my first article on DeckTech, so please be kind.  This article is entirely theoretical, as I do not have the cards to make the deck nor the ability as a player to make it work.  Finally, I go to art school so please make your criticism mean something, and not just be &quot;I like it&quot; or &quot;Its nice&quot; (like some people at my school insist on doing).<br>
<br>
And Now on to the Meat...<br>
All shadow decks run on some sort of attrition, be it fierce battles, archery or swarms (swarms is an oddity of attrition because it is based on overwhelming rather than damage, however the constant barrage of attacks fits the definition of attrition).  The ability to make every wound matter is an important part of LotR:TCG.  But, how often have you lost because you decided to double move, or that important site was taken by Thor&#39;s Map.  Is the simple act of movement a danger within itself?  I hope so because the game seems to be designed around this assumption.<br>
What sights are the most dangerous moves?  Its obviously not site 2 to 3, and site 6 to 7 isn&#39;t that bad (hopefully you just had a significant heal session at the sanctuary).  So what&#39;s left?  Site 8 to 9 is obviously the last hurrah of the shadow.  Site 5 is the Balrog in all his glory.  Site 3 to 4 is the first real chance for the shadow to slow down the fellowship.  Site 7 to 8 is when the damage has to come down for there to be any real chance at site 9.  And finally the initial move from site 1 to site 2.<br>
<br>
Attrition is the &quot;wearing away of resistance by constant attacks.&quot;  At each move the fellowship should be facing the loss of one of its members.  The fellowships initial move is quite important.  Many players make a somewhat safe assumption that the early game is the time to create the foundation for the fellowship.  The first fellowship turn often finds itself deploying many companions, allies, weapons, etc. in the relative safety of the first move.  With the increase of twilight in the first turn the shadow gets an opportunity for an early kill.  The Ringwraiths certainly gain the advantage of this move with their early home site, though there are plenty of options.  Archers can put in some early hurt, and the Watcher gets its first chance to come out and play.<br>
<br>
Now a few obvious criticisms deserve to be noted.  First I am purposefully ignoring &quot;Pipe Weed&quot; decks, as well as Glamdring and Sting, their ability to decrease the twilight pool diminishes the ability of this theory to do any damage.  Next is the some quick math, how much damage can someone do at site two?  With a fairly common and standard start of Arwen, Legolas, with Aragorn played from deck and moving to site 2 Midgewater Marshes is 4 twilight for Aragorn, 4 for the fellowship and 1 for the sight making 9 twilight, ignoring weapons, conditions, allies, or any other costs that may occur; to deploy a Huge Tentacle and the Watcher, 10 twilight is needed, which any weapon can make.  <br>
<br>
Sight 2 to 3 is fairly safe except for one thing &quot;Ford of Bruinen.&quot;  The -5 to the first Nazguel can create further damage from sight 2.  A shadow that didn&#39;t lose someone at site 2 could receive that early death at 3.  Of course, for every pro there is a con.  The &quot;Ford&quot; is a river meaning a simple death could occur for the one or two Nazguel that do get played (three or more at site 3 would take a lot of twilight which could happen but is not likely).<br>
<br>
Site 3 to 4 is still fairly safe.  The fellowship has just healed, probably recouped losses and a turn or two has occurred to cycle their hand into something useful (by now weapons are almost certain, and events are probably in hand to put the hurt on the shadow).  The fate of the fellowship after site 3 is really decided here.  If we keep the assumption that Arwen, Legolas, and Aragorn is the fellowship there is a guaranteed 7 twilight.  What can be done with seven?  At site four Moria stops roaming, and at Hollin Uruk-Hai stop roaming.  Nazguel are still going strong and Sauron are still taking the roaming penalties to the throat.  Seven is enough to get the Watcher out with a Tentacle, add a runner and you get an extra tentacle.  Moria archery gets the &quot;Great Chasm&quot; making the twilight essentially 10 (because the &quot;Chasm&quot; is 4 twilight instead of 3), and the swarms get more than enough to get 20 or 30 minions out (I kid because I care).  The Uruk&#39;s can get Lurtz out, and the Ringwraiths can almost get a Witch King. The damage of this site is not necessarily for the possible deaths (though these are always nice), its the preparation for site 5.<br>
<br>
Site 5, everyone knows it, everyone loves it, everyone hates it.  The dreaded Balrog.  Never before has the ability to kill a character been easier.  We all know what he does so on to the attrition.  There is going to be either exertions to cancel skirmishes, wounds, stealths (the worst pain is seeing Sam run from the Balrog), or deaths (the best joy is seeing Sam eaten by the Balrog).  What does this mean for the attrition deck?  Hopefully a death, one less mook to kill, or, the worst of the good, more than 5 wounds, or nothing (which just plain sucks).<br>
<br>
On to site 6!  This is the last chance for the shadow to do any real damage to the Fellowship before healing and the final run.  This is were Moria decks rule.  &quot;Dimrill Dale&quot; again gives the virtual +2 to the shadow but now it is not limited to the archers.  Our test fellowship again gives seven to the pool, and now no one roams.  Because I have been ignoring virtually the Uruk&#39;s and Sauron, I will summarize what should be happening at the average deck with no tricks or trades.  Uruk&#39;s should be giving 2 wounds a shadow phase and possibly adding some burdens with &quot;Worry.&quot;  Sauron should be setting up their conditions and triggering them, usually by playing a minion or two to trigger Bowmen, Thin and Stretched and Desperate Defense.<br>
<br>
A site 6 to 7 is much like sites 3 to 4.  The shadow just needs to start the hurt.  This is also when the sites start to get more dangerous.  The higher twilight to move and the more damaging sight conditions make it much more challenging to get through.  Sites like the &quot;confluence&quot; and the &quot;banks&quot; can cause the first of a long road of pain.  Hobbit healing circle can be destroyed, and non-ranger decks get the first in the long road to hurt.  The shadow should be doing what it does, and hopefully fairly well.<br>
<br>
And now the long haul sites 8 and 9.  By know all you readers out there have probably noticed that my analysis is getting a bit thin.  This is from the fact that by these sights your deck should be set up and doing what it does.  These are the last chance for the fellowship to be damaged.  If it isn&#39;t happening by know the only advice I can give is:  &quot;run, run like you have never run before, run like the world championships are on the line, there is no other option, just run.&quot;<br>
<br>
Practical Application:<br>
Until now this has been a theoretical article.  Basic explanation of what each move can mean.  But what of the practical application of this theory?  How can your deck be built to use this theory to its maximum potential?  Here is a sample shadow and the beginnings of an adventure path to give an idea with an explanation (of course).<br>
<br>
First of all the Balrog is going into the deck, he is the best chance for the shadow to cause enough damage before site 6 to make the attrition matter.  Next we&#39;ll make the deck Moria Archery, so we don&#39;t have to rely entirely on winning skirmishes or overwhelming.  Finally we&#39;ll toss in a couple of watchers and tentacles to make a strong chance for an early death.<br>
<br>
So the deck looks a little something like this before reductions and substitutions:<br>
2 Watcher in the Water<br>
4 Huge Tentacles<br>
4 Foul Tentacles<br>
1 Balrog Flame of Udun<br>
1 Balrog Durins Bane<br>
4 Moria Archery Troops<br>
4 Goblin Bowman<br>
4 Goblin Marksmen<br>
4 Archer Commander<br>
4 Goblin Archer<br>
4 Goblin Runners<br>
4 They Are Coming<br>
<br>
Now thats a staggering 40 card shadow, which could work but lets cut it down and see what can be done.  First we only need 2 huge tentacles.  The Goblin Archer is overpriced and under abilities though we should keep one or two so there goes 2 more cards.  The Archer Commander is unique so we only need 2 of him.  There is no reason to have more than 3 They Are Coming, and I frankly don&#39;t like the card, so I&#39;m only going to run 2.  The deck now looks something like this:<br>
2 Watcher in the Water<br>
2 Huge Tentacles<br>
4 Foul Tentacles<br>
1 Balrog Flame of Udun<br>
1 Balrog Durins Bane<br>
4 Moria Archery Troops<br>
4 Goblin Bowman<br>
4 Goblin Marksmen<br>
2 Archer Commander<br>
2 Goblin Archer<br>
4 Goblin Runners<br>
2 They Are Coming<br>
<br>
--A quick note:  the reason to run both Balrog&#39;s is in case there is no way to spot a Moria Orc or there is not enough pool (which I have seen)<br>
<br>
Thus making the deck a reasonable 32 cards.  In addition to the shadow the adventure path should include:<br>
<br>
Midgewater Marshes and Moria Lake for the Watcher (the only reason to run 2 Watchers)<br>
Dimrill Dale for the archers<br>
Brown Lands for more archery<br>
<br>
One possible alteration is the inclusion of several nazguel and the Ford for some early hurt.  As for the Fellowship thats up to you.  There does need good flow but thats true in any deck so be sure to think it through.<br>
<br>
Thats all, thanks for sticking around for this rather lengthy article and sorry if I put it up twice.<br>
Anthony Tonies_Gin Gin<br>
